6. Literature Review (≈ 1.5 pages)
The SPICE toolkit has been extensively used in planetary missions by NASA, ESA, JAXA, and ISRO since the 1990s. It provides robust functions for ephemeris calculations, frame transformations, time conversions, and geometry finder (GF) routines that detect events such as occultations, eclipses, rise/set times, and field-of-view intersections.
Most existing implementations are script-based (using CSPICE, Python SpiceyPy, or MATLAB) and targeted at expert users. Very few attempts have been made to develop graphical or web-based interfaces for SPICE. Available tools are usually desktop applications or specialized mission-planning software with limited accessibility.
This project contributes by combining the accuracy of the SPICE toolkit with modern web technologies (JSP + ASP.NET), making high-precision geometric computations available through a browser-based interface. It fills the gap between powerful backend computation and user-friendly frontend interaction.

7. Methodology (≈ 2 pages)
The system follows a modular client-server architecture:
Step 1: Input Collection
Users provide parameters through web forms — time range (UTC or TDB), observer body, target body, event type (e.g., occultation, eclipse), and other constraints.
Step 2: Frontend Processing
JSP pages collect inputs and use iframe for smooth navigation between different modules (Input, Computation, Results, History).
Step 3: Backend Processing
ASP.NET (ASPX + C# code-behind) receives the request, validates inputs, prepares SPICE commands or calls the SPICE library, and executes geometric event computations.
Step 4: Database Handling
MySQL database stores:

User session/input data
Computation parameters
Generated results for future reference

Step 5: Output Generation
Results (time windows, event duration, geometry parameters) are formatted and displayed on the web interface in tabular or graphical form.

